<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><br /></div><div><br /></div><div><span style="font-size: 18px; font-weight: bold;">Adding the Custom Widget Areas</span></div><div>Note: All the <span style="color: rgb(255, 47, 146);">red</span> colors are the WP builtin Function!</div><div><br /></div><div><span style="font-weight: bold;">Step1</span>.<span style="color: rgb(146, 146, 146);"> Edit the “functions.php” file:</span></div><div><span style="color: rgb(146, 146, 146);">          // Create the function: You can give any name you like:</span></div><div><span style="color: rgb(146, 146, 146);">          // “name” - will show up as a widget area</span></div><div><span style="color: rgb(146, 146, 146);">         //  “id”  is the internal variable you make reference to call later</span></div><div>            <span style="color: rgb(255, 64, 255);">function</span> <span style="color: rgb(0, 150, 255);">KFH_Widgets_Area()</span> <span style="color: rgb(255, 64, 255); font-weight: bold;">{</span></div><div>                <span style="color: rgb(255, 47, 146);">register_sidebar(</span> <span style="color: rgb(0, 144, 81);">array (</span></div><div>                ‘<span style="color: rgb(148, 82, 0);">name</span>’ =&gt; ‘<span style="color: rgb(146, 144, 0);">Sidebar</span>’</div><div>                ‘<span style="color: rgb(148, 82, 0);">id</span>’ =&gt; ‘<span style="color: rgb(146, 144, 0);">my_sidebar</span>’</div><div>                <span style="color: rgb(0, 144, 81);"> )</span><span style="color: rgb(255, 47, 146);">)</span>;</div><div>          <span style="color: rgb(255, 64, 255); font-weight: bold;">  }</span></div><div><span style="font-weight: bold;">Step 2</span>.<span style="color: rgb(146, 146, 146);"> Let the WordPress know about your function:</span></div><div><span style="color: rgb(146, 146, 146);">            // Add this line after your function definition:</span></div><div>            <span style="color: rgb(255, 47, 146);">add_action(</span>‘<span style="color: rgb(255, 47, 146);">widgets_init</span>’, ‘<span style="color: rgb(0, 150, 255);">KFH_Widgets_Area</span>’<span style="color: rgb(255, 47, 146);">)</span>;</div><div><br /></div><div><span style="font-weight: bold;">Step 3</span>.<span style="color: rgb(146, 146, 146);"> Create an area in your page where you want to insert the widgets.</span></div><div><span style="color: rgb(146, 146, 146);">            In my case, I had the “sidebar.php” section and I put the following code</span></div><div><span style="color: rgb(146, 146, 146);">            inside the &lt;div&gt; tag:</span></div><div>           <span style="color: rgb(148, 17, 0);"> &lt;aside</span><span style="color: rgb(0, 84, 147);"> class</span>="<span style="color: rgb(148, 55, 255);">sidebar</span>"&gt;</div><div>                <span style="color: rgb(255, 64, 255);">&lt;?php</span> <span style="color: rgb(255, 47, 146);">dynamic_sidebar</span>('<span style="color: rgb(146, 144, 0);">my_sidebar</span>'); <span style="color: rgb(255, 64, 255);">?&gt;</span></div><div>           <span style="color: rgb(148, 17, 0);"> </span><span style="color: rgb(148, 17, 0);">&lt;/aside&gt;</span></div><div><br /></div><div>Adding the Edit Botton to the end of a Post</div><div><br /></div><div><span style="color: rgb(148, 17, 0);">&lt;article </span><span style="color: rgb(4, 51, 255);">class</span>="<span style="color: rgb(0, 143, 0);">post</span>"&gt;</div><div>       <span style="color: rgb(255, 64, 255);">&lt;?php</span> <span style="color: rgb(255, 47, 146);">the_content()</span>;<span style="color: rgb(255, 64, 255);"> ?&gt;</span></div><div>      <span style="color: rgb(255, 64, 255);"> &lt;?php</span> <span style="color: rgb(255, 47, 146);">edit_post_link</span>(‘<span style="color: rgb(0, 150, 255);">Edit</span>', '<span style="font-weight: bold;">&lt;p&gt;</span>', '<span style="font-weight: bold;">&lt;/p&gt;</span>');<span style="color: rgb(255, 64, 255);"> ?&gt;</span></div><div><span style="color: rgb(148, 17, 0);">&lt;/article&gt;</span></div><div><br /></div><div><b><font style="font-size: 18px;">How to Add the Date, Author and Category in a Post</font></b></div><div><br /></div><div>The HTML Part: “index.php” file</div><div>- The code starts just after the &lt;h2&gt; tag.</div><div>- Ends just before we read the content of the post.</div><div>- If we wanted to make a permalink to the author,  we could have the code:</div><div>  <font color="#ff40ff">&lt;?php</font><font color="#ff2f92"> the_author():</font> <font color="#ff40ff">?&gt;</font></div><div>            to</div><div><font color="#9437ff">&lt;a href</font>=“<font color="#ff40ff">&lt;?php</font><font color="#ff85ff"> </font><font color="#ff2f92">get_author_posts_url</font>(<font color="#929000">get_the_author_meta</font>(‘<font color="#941100">ID</font>’)) <font color="#ff40ff">?&gt;</font>”<font color="#9437ff">&gt;</font><font color="#ff40ff">&lt;?php </font><font color="#ff2f92">the_author()</font>; <font color="#ff40ff">?&gt;</font> <font color="#9437ff">&lt;/a&gt;</font></div><div><br /></div><div><en-media hash="4ebae501279061d210b231c7ebc76c05" type="image/png" /></div><div><br /></div><div>The CSS Part:</div><div>- We removed the space below &lt;h2&gt; and above &lt;p&gt; tags</div><div><br /></div><div><en-media hash="8a5f6a0a8cb96439a66f89584bded9b7" type="image/png" /></div><div><br /></div><div><br /></div><div><br /></div><div><br /></div></en-note>